# Project TryBlynx — Implementation Plan

## Goal

Build a production-grade, zero-cost-infrastructure chat and social platform targeting **10,000–20,000 concurrent WebSocket connections**. The system uses **Go WebSockets** for real-time messaging, **Redis** for state/Pub-Sub, **PostgreSQL** for persistence (own instance, not Supabase — no 200-connection ceiling), **WebRTC + Coturn** for video, and **Stripe** for VIP payments. Every WebSocket connection is JWT-secured; shadowbanned users are silently quarantined; and Stripe webhooks are cryptographically verified. **Backend API only** — no frontend UI generated.

---

## User Review Required

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Stripe Keys**: The webhook endpoint and checkout session creation require your Stripe Secret Key and Webhook Signing Secret. These will be read from environment variables (`STRIPE_SECRET_KEY`, `STRIPE_WEBHOOK_SECRET`). You will need a Stripe account and test-mode keys.

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Coturn / TURN Server**: The plan includes WebRTC signaling via the Go WebSocket server. A Coturn TURN server container is included in Docker Compose for NAT traversal. You may replace this with a hosted TURN provider if preferred.

> [!WARNING]
> **JWT Secret**: A single symmetric HMAC-SHA256 secret (`JWT_SECRET` env var) is used for signing and verifying tokens. For production, consider rotating secrets or switching to asymmetric RS256 keys.

